It is hard to see Russia officially recognising Transnistria and endangering itself with a conflict with Moldova that will possible ask military assistance from Romania, without occupying the parts of Ukraine between Russia and Transnistria. Although Russia declared getting a land corridor to Transnistria as one of its military targets, achieving it before August 2022 seems impossible at the moment.

The Russian army in Transnistria cannot be supplied or reinforced. Putin stirring up any kind of trouble there is the equivalent of his asking for a humiliating defeat. Moldova would almost certainly take steps to strangle any Transnistrian republic that claimed sovereignty, and the West would guarantee its victory. Russian troops in Transnistria would of course resist any Moldovan effort to reassert control, but again, the Russians can't be supplied or reinforced, so in the end Transnistria would just be a Russian Dien Bien Phu.

The Russian campaign in southwestern Ukraine is stalled, and to some extent being pushed back. The proposed linkup with Transnistria, or an attempt to move against Odessa are not happening any time soon. It looks like the theater of war is entirely in the east, and I would not be surprised if the Russians had to withdraw behind the Dnieper in the southwest in order to concentrate their efforts in Luhansk/Donetsk. Recognition of Transnistria as an independent republic would simply open a new front that Russia could not supply or reinforce. Since Putin appears to be hesitant to mobilize Russian society for all-out (conventional) war, a recognition of Transnistria would be a provocation that would expose weakness, not strength. You don't open a new front that you can't support, and that will probably be overrun without your demonstrating any ability to prevent it.

Forecasts on this question are all over the place but I think the odds are slightly in favor of this. From a military operational perspective, it's a weak and risky position: difficult to supply, difficult to defend, difficult to launch any major offensive from. From a geopolitical perspective, it could serve as a useful hedge against Ukrainian offensive ops. It forces Ukraine to pay attention to Russian movements along a much longer border. It's also simplifies any Russian withdrawal from Transnistria if the war goes badly in in eastern Ukraine. Seems like a cheap way to gain some positive results (by their logic) and easy to abandon if overall geopolitical results turn negative.

I think it still seems quite unlikely that Transnistria will be recognised as an independent state by Russia soon because Russia does not have any way of actually getting troops there to assert that recognition, and the troops that are already there do not have the capabilities to do anything on their own. Most likely, I think the recent noise there is more about keeping it relevant as a possible trump card if the conflict lasts and Russia perhaps gets a foot in Odessa rather than because there is a short term plan to recognise Transnistria as an independent state.

The Russians appear to have given up on Kyiv, and my guess is that they have given up on Odessa too. I always thought that Odessa was a long shot for them, given the flat, muddy farmland, multiple river crossings, and the need to stick to major roads. So I think the whole ambition of Russia taking and absorbing Ukraine's southwest has pretty much evaporated. The action now will be in Luhansk/Donetsk, Kherson and Zaporizhia as the Russians try to pull out a victory by linking Crimea with Luhansk/Donetsk. I don't expect them to withdraw from the Odessa front, just to consolidate their holdings there as a bargaining chip. In my opinion, Putin will try to negotiate at the very least a cease-fire in place once Mariupol falls, and perhaps offer a pullback behind the lower Dnieper to sweeten the deal. This will freeze the conflict, if not end it, and for Putin 's failures in Kyiv and elsewhere he can use the old Pee-Wee Herman excuse when he suffers a particularly humiliating pratfall: "I meant to do that."

I think the South Ossetian referendum being planned proves Russia isn't afraid to go for it even though they're already bogged down. The main question is whether Russia manages to annex all of the Black Sea coast in the next four months, which seems unlikely. They probably have to win in Donbas and Kyiv before they are likely to bother, and that's hard. But four months is a long time and I'm convinced the mens rea is already there. I wouldn't totally put it past them recognizing independence prior to creating the necessary land bridge, but I would give that low single digit odds.

Now properly understanding this question; my thoughts are that this is a low-cost, potentially high-reward action for Putin insofar as it could help him garner further support domestically. Alternatively, news from the Ukraine-Russian conflict indicates the Russians are potentially looking to moderate their claims in Ukraine as it has proved a more difficult undertaking than they had likely anticipated. On one hand, further recognition of independent statelets within other countries probably doesn't do much for a Russian state looking to capitulate on their demands in Ukraine and attempt a normalization. On the other hand, this is a means of potentially (appearing to) advance the initiative, again that costs Putin essentially nothing except potentially some of the goodwill of his Western interlocutors.

Thoughts about base rate of reference class (breakaway territories that seeked recognition by/integration into Russia): four of them (two in Georgia and two in Ukraine) have been recognized by Russia by now. Transnistria is the last remaining to my knowledge. Choosing a timeframe is not straightforward: if the disintegration of the UdSSR ist taken as a beginning, the annual probality is relatively low with 4 recognitions in roughly three decades. Shorter-time frames could be applied (since Putin is in power - roughly two decades; since the first recognitions - a bit more than 1 decade) . However, none of them would suggest a high probability of the next recognition within a few months as th e average rate in the shortest time frame is roughly one recognition every three years.

If Putin succeeds in conquering Ukraine, Moldova would be an easy pickup. However, an invasion, at least at this time, would seem unlikely as Moldova is a NATO member. At the same time, it is pretty clear that part of the strategy in invading Ukraine is to test the resolve of NATO. Declaring Transnistria independent will be the next logical step, basically declaring a part of NATO is not really in NATO, to test the alliance. It makes more sense than invading Eastern Poland (a NATO member) to gain a land bridge to Kaliningrad, invading the Baltic Countries (Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania, all NATO members), or invading Finland (a non-NATO member that appears to be reversing course on their longstanding NATO v. Russia neutrality by expressing interest in NATO membership if Sweden applied at the same time).

Putin has made more erratic decisions than this one in the past couple of weeks, so this one, which would serve him tactically in the narrative of "peace keeping" is far from unlikely.

Recently, a Belorussian video showed what appeared to be a map of Ukraine- part of which detailed an arrow directed from Southern Ukraine, towards Moldova (Transnistria). The question is what concrete goal would this achieve? There are already Russian troops in Transnistria and have been for decades. Transnistria is functionally independent already, and it is unlikely the status quo is going to be changed by Moldovan action any time soon. Moldova is constitutionally prohibited from joining NATO, so that issue is moot (for now - could change). Transnistria does not have notable economic resources, and only has about 300,000 people, so the cost/benefit is relatively high.

If I were Vlad the Shirtless (I'm not; I need the pockets) I'd go ahead and do this. The monetary cost is roughly zero, and the additional geopolitical and reputational cost is decimal dust. Simply recognizing Transnistria as an independent state doesn't obligate anybody to do anything for or about them. Neither Russia nor any other state is obligated to invade every place they recognize as independent.
